    "title": "Integrative Close: The Anatomy of a Cable",
    "objective": "Synthesize atomic theory with the practical properties of conductors and insulators to explain electrical behavior.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Consider a standard electrical cable consisting of a copper internal core and a PVC (plastic) outer sheath.",
      "Recall how the 'grip' of the nucleus on valence electrons differs between metals and non-metals.",
      "Think about what must happen at an atomic level for a material to allow or resist the flow of current."
    ],
    "questionText": "In a standard electrical cable, the copper core and the PVC insulation perform opposite roles. Explain how the atomic structure of these two materials—specifically the state of the electrons in their valence shells—determines why one allows current to flow while the other prevents it.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Copper is a conductor because its valence electrons are loosely held by the nucleus, allowing them to break away and become 'free electrons' that move to form a current.",
      "PVC is an insulator because its valence electrons are tightly bound to the nucleus, meaning there are no free electrons available to carry an electrical charge.",
      "The difference in behavior is defined by whether the material's atomic structure permits the movement of free electrons."
    ],
    "hint": "Focus on the 'grip' of the nucleus and whether the electrons in the outermost shell are 'free' or 'bound'."
  }
}

